<!-- Borrowed from ORCCA section-compound-inequalities: Compound Inequalities -->
  
  <exercises>
    <title>ORCCA exercises</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ORCCA-UP3AUebzsG" license="CC-BY-4.0">
              <statement>
                  <p>Solve the compound inequality. <me>-6\ge 3x+3\quad\text{and}\quad3x+9\gt-6</me></p>
              </statement>
              <solution>
                  <p><md>
                      <mrow>-6\amp\ge 3x+3\amp\text{and}\amp\amp 3x+9\amp\gt -6</mrow>
                      <mrow>-9\amp\ge 3x\amp\text{and}\amp\amp 3x\amp\gt -15</mrow>
                      <mrow>-3\amp\ge x\amp\text{and}\amp\amp x\amp\gt -5</mrow>
                      <mrow>\highlight{x}\amp\mathbin{\highlight{\le}}\highlight{-3}\amp\text{and}\amp\amp x\amp\gt -5</mrow>
                  </md></p>
                  <p>The solution set to <m>x\le -3</m> is <m>(-\infty,-3]</m> and the solution set to <m>x\gt-5</m> is <m>(-5,\infty)</m>. Shown is a graph of these solution sets on a number line.</p>
  
                  <figure xml:id="ORCCA-demkA5Y03L" license="CC-BY-4.0">
                  <caption>A number line sketch of <m>(-\infty,-3]</m> and <m>(-5,\infty)</m></caption>
                      <image width="47%">
                      <shortdescription>a number line where the numbers 0, -3, and -5 are marked; a thick line is above the x-axis starting at -3 with a right bracket and going to the left with an arrow; another thick line is above the axis starting at -5 with a left parenthesis and going to the right with an arrow.</shortdescription>
                             <latex-image>
                              \begin{tikzpicture}
                                  \begin{axis}[numberline, xmin=-10, xmax=1, xtick={-3,-5}, minor xtick={-10,-9,...,1}]
                                      \addplot[infiniteclosedinterval] coordinates {(-10,0.4) (-3,0.4)};
                                      \addplot[openinfiniteinterval, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(-5,1) (1,1)};
                                  \end{axis}
                              \end{tikzpicture}
                          </latex-image>
                         </image>
                  </figure>
                  <p>Recall that <q>and</q> statements of inequalities become intersections of the solution sets. Since intersections refer to where the sets overlap, and these sets overlap between <m>-5</m> (exclusive) and <m>-3</m> (inclusive), we would say <me>(-\infty,-3]\cap(-5,\infty)=(-5,-3]</me>.</p>
              </solution>
          </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ORCCA-CC1TSEUMPy" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the difference between an <q>inequality</q> and a <q>compound inequality</q>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ORCCA-eEgq85vlRz" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the difference between a union and an intersection?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ORCCA-7dtzfGo3wf" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain why <m>-3\lt5\ge2</m> doesn't make mathematical sense.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ORCCA-i5z9A3bSWv" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If you solve a compound inequality and your final simplification is <q><m>x\gt7\text{ and }x\lt12</m></q>,
            how many solutions are in your solution set?
            How would you write those solutions?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    <exercise><statement><p>Webwork Omitted</p></statement></exercise>
    <exercise><statement><p>Webwork Omitted</p></statement></exercise>
    <exercise><statement><p>Webwork Omitted</p></statement></exercise>
    <exercise><statement><p>Webwork Omitted</p></statement></exercise>
    <exercise><statement><p>Webwork Omitted</p></statement></exercise>
